The General Assembly finds that:
The chief cause of skin cancer is exposure to ultraviolet rays from natural sunlight and artificial sources;
According to the American Cancer Society, skin cancer is one (1) of the most common types of cancer in the United States, with one (1) in five (5) Americans developing skin cancer in his or her lifetime and one (1) American dying from skin cancer every hour;
The lifetime risk of getting skin cancer is linked to sun exposure and sunburn during childhood and adolescence;
World and national health organizations have published guidelines or instructional materials regarding sun safety and skin cancer prevention for schools; and
Schools have the potential to positively influence pupil behavior regarding skin cancer prevention.
